Executive Summary¶

We are creating a way to see how accurate regression models are on the data from a research project when the increments of when the temperature are taken are further apart. We first found the ideal degree to use on our original data set and plotted a regression model to see what we were comparing to. We then created a function that determined the $r^2$ value of a regression model when every $1/n$ of the original temperatures and times are included. For our final step, we plotted the $r^2$ values to see what increments are best to keep a similar model to our original. From this model we were able to determine that if the temperature was taken every 3.5 days at a depth of 2 meters, the model would have a $r^2$ of around 0.6 which is close to our original $r^2$ value of 0.72. We suggest that the model would work better if it could take in more specific values and if it could be tested on an area that has more temperature fluctuation.

Ethical Considerations¶

As this data is taken in a sceintific context, it is hard to find bias within it. As the research project is trying to find a disparity between temperatures at different depths, it is important to note that this fact may have played a role in the chosen location. Another motivation around choosing the location of the research project was an additional project to see how the different temperatures impact intertidal mussels and barnacles.

Introduction¶

This project aims to approximate how often it is necessary to measure ocean temperature for accurate results. Our motivation behind obtaining such measurements is due to increasing ocean temperatures. Currently, ocean temperature is measured aerially, and it is more accurate to measure it at specific depths which is what our device is measuring. As this device is a newer technology, it is more expensive to use and since the temperature is taken every ten minutes, the device has to sit in the same area for prolonged periods of time. As it is crucial to measure ocean temperature accurately in the whole ocean to monitor the effects of climate change, cost effectiveness and resource allocation are issues to consider with this device. The goal of this project is to create a more cost effective way for the scientists to measure the temperature and we believe a similar temperature model can be created when the temperature is taken in less frequent increments than every 10 minutes.

Data Description¶

Our datasets were taken from a study currently being conducted in Carrie Bow Bay, Belize by a Northeastern PhD student. We had four different datasets, each corresponding to a depth of either two, five, ten, or twenty meters below the oceans surface. The data is measured by a temperature-measuring device, and temperatures were recorded every 10 minutes from 2000 - 2012. In addition to temperature data in Celsius, the datasets contained information about the location, which was very consistent within and across the datasets; reef habitat; depth, which was consistent within datasets; and time of day. An example of our original dataset is shown below.

We then separated the time information, which was originally formatted as M/D/YYYY 00:00, by using several functions that created separate columns for year, month, day, hour, minute, and second such that each row had distinct integer values for each of these variables. More Pipelining of Data for Regression¶

We can see from the above graph that when we remove the rows that don't contain any values(NaN), it gets rid of the data from 2008 to 2011 which means we should narrow the amount of data we are looking at to a time range in which the data was collected consistently. We decided to choose a year as the period of time we wanted to apply our regression model to as we believed that a year was a good amount of time to test our data on as temperature seems to fluctuate in similar ways annually. We specifically chose the year 2000 because we believed that the first year that the data was taken was going to be the data that was collected in the most consistent way.

Before we did that, we wanted to make sure that the data was split into columns of year, month, day, hour, minute, and second in order to use those columns as features later. We also had to turn the values within those columns into integers or floats in order for them to work later.

Method¶

We decided to use polynomial regression to accurately depict a graphical representation of our data and create a prediction for future temperatures. Since our data fluctuates with the time of day and the seasons, a polynomial regression makes more sense than a simple linear regression as it can follow the curve and pattern of the data better. Additionally, we decided against a random forest classifier or a decision tree as our data would be more visually informative in the form of a regression line (because were only predicting temperature based on depths). Since the data does follow more of a wave-like pattern this type of regression may prove difficult since we have't learned how to apply regression for data that looks like that.

Polynomial Determination¶

A differentiator between polynomial regression and linear regression is that a polynomial regression doesnt need the relationship between temperature and depth to be linear. First, we fitted our regression model to our data (specifically, we analyzed year, month, day, hour, minute, second, and temperature in Celsius) and cross-validated it using KFold to test and train our data. We used the r^2 score to find the best polynomial degree for our data, and then split the data frame into a multitude of time intervals (20, 30, and 60 minutes) based on user input. Then, we graphed our polynomial regression model so we could examine how a model using different time increments would compare to our original 10 minute graph.

In [15]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import PolynomialFeatures
from sklearn.model_selection import KFold
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.metrics import r2_score
from tqdm import tqdm

# defines features used
x = df_two_m_years.loc[:, ['year','month', 'day', 'hour', 'minute', 'second']]
y = df_two_m_years['temp_c'].values

# determines splots and maz degree
n_splits = 10
max_degree = 9

# init cross validation & regression obj
lin_reg = LinearRegression(fit_intercept=False)
kfold = KFold(n_splits=n_splits, shuffle=True)

# designates r2 dict to add values to
r2_dict = dict()
# tests degrees from 1 to 9
for degree in tqdm(range(1, max_degree)):
    # project into polynomial features of proper degree
    poly_feat = PolynomialFeatures(degree=degree)
    x_poly = poly_feat.fit_transform(x)

    # cross validation loop
    y_pred = np.empty_like(y)
    for train_idx, test_idx in kfold.split(x):
        # split data into train / test
        x_poly_train = x_poly[train_idx, :]
        x_poly_test = x_poly[test_idx, :]
        y_train = y[train_idx]
        
        # fit from train data, predict from test
        lin_reg.fit(x_poly_train, y_train)
        y_pred[test_idx] = lin_reg.predict(x_poly_test)
        
    # compute / store cross validated r2 score
    r2_dict[degree] = r2_score(y_pred=y_pred, y_true=y)

Model¶

In polynomial regression, its assumed that a curved linear relationship between the dependent variable (temperature) and the independent variable (depth) explains the behavior of the temperature. However, a downfall of this method is the ease of under-fitting or over-fitting if we choose the wrong degree. We want our regression line to accurately reflect the current data so we can predict future data (if its too simple, it cant explain the variance), but at the same time, if its too accurate, its too good to be true.

# used from lecture slides

def coef_to_poly_str(coef, include_zero=False):
    """ creates a str of polynomial corresponding to coef    

    Args:
        coef (np.array): coefficients of polynomial
        
    Returns:
        poly_str (str): str of polynomial
    """
    # designates list to add values to
    str_monomial_list = []
    
    for deg, coef in enumerate(coef):
        if coef == 0 and include_zero == False:
            # this coefficient is zero, just skip it altogether
            continue
            
        # turns the coefficient into a string
        str_monomial_list.append(f'{coef:+.1f} x^{deg:d}')
        
    # returns the equation a string
    return 'y = ' + ' '.join(str_monomial_list)

Results¶

Estimation¶

This shows our $r^2$ value from the regression model above when we plot the regression against the data before it was put into increments. We will use this score to determine at what point is a $r^2$ value a good $r^2$ value when the increments are taken out. We don't want the value we get to be too far away from the original value.

Function¶

In [21]:
def interval_regress(divider):
    """ divides the data into intervals and finds the r2 value of 
    the regression compared to the regression of the original data
    
    Args:
        divider(int): the intervals of 10 the data is split into
    """
    # separates the data by every into increments determined by the divider
    new_df = df_two_m_years.iloc[::divider, :]
    
    # designates the degree of the regression
    degree = 2

    # defines the x and y values
    x = new_df.loc[:, ['year','month', 'day', 'hour', 'minute', 'second']]
    y = new_df['temp_c'].values
    
    # fit polynomial regression
    poly_feat = PolynomialFeatures(degree=degree)
    x_poly = poly_feat.fit_transform(x)

    # predict y (from regression)
    y_pred = reg.predict(x_poly)
    
    # calculates the r2 score 
    r2_val = r2_score(y_pred=y_pred, y_true=y)
    
    return r2_val

Validation¶

To find the best increments to take temperature in, we compute the cross-validated $r^2$ value for increments from 1 to 2500 to see which $r^2$.

  • If this value is close to 1, then the time increment of temperature taken will create a similar model to the original model.
  • If this value is close to zero, then the time increment of temperature taken will not create a similar enough model.
  • If this value is negative, then the time increment of temperature taken will be nothing like the original model.

Discussion¶

The results showed that our prediction model was accurate, with an $r^2$ score of 0.717. With this model, we could answer our original question of how often a temperature measurement is necessary to get an accurate result using a function that calculated the $r^2$ of models on the data when increments were removed. Using the function, we saw that a dropoff below 0.6 in $r^2$ only occurred at around 500 ten-minute increments or 3.5 days. Since at this increment the $r^2$ score was around 0.6, we could say it was close to our original model because it is only a 0.117 decrease in $r^2$ and still is close to the ideal value of 1. This is significant since our original dataset measured temperature every ten minutes and our results show that measuring every 3.5 days would not substantially affect the results.

The challenges we faced during our project were mainly with our data. The dataset we used was very simple and we could only use temperature for our analysis. This made our options limited in terms of any graphs or research on the data. Our group also had trouble when constructing the machine-learning part of the project, specifically when calculating the $r^2$ score of the model. It also was fairly confusing that the best degree for our data was determined to be 2 because there was clearly more than 2 degrees once we plotted our regression line.

Takeaway:¶

These results are significant since measuring the temperature less often and still getting accurate data would reduce the overall cost of the project making the temperature taking device more cost effective. The cost to maintain the measuring device would certainly go down and it could even be moved to other locations in the time between measurements. This would save money and time in projects where measurements in several locations are needed. These results were both expected and unexpected to our team because we agreed that measurements every ten minutes were unnecessary, but we did not expect that measurements every three and a half days would be around as accurate.

One question we would like to answer before implementing any change would be how accurate is the model on locations other than Belize. Would a colder climate change the results? Would a more volatile climate change the results? That way, we could be more confident in our prediction in locations around the world. It would also be ideal if our function was modified to take in values that are more specific than increments of ten (as in days, weeks, years, etc.)

def remove_time(data):
    data.dropna(axis = 0, inplace = True)
    data_list = []
    for t in data.loc[:,'time_gmt']:
        date, time = t.split(" ")
        data_list.append(date)
    data['time_gmt'] = data_list
    return data


def remove_day(data):
    date_list = []
    year_list = []
    for t in data.loc[:,'time_gmt']:
        year, month,day = t.split("-")
        date_list.append(str(year) + '-' +str(month))
        #year_list.append(year)
        
    data['time_gmt'] = date_list
    return data

def iso_year(data,target_year):
    temp_dict = defaultdict(lambda:0)
    for i in range(len(data)):
         if int(data.index[i].split('-')[0]) == target_year:
            temp_dict[data.index[i]] = data.loc[data.index[i],'temp_c']
            
    return temp_dict

def plot(temp_dict,label):
    plt.scatter(x = temp_dict.keys(),y= temp_dict.values(), label = label)
    plt.plot(temp_dict.keys(),temp_dict.values())
